'''Francesco (Frank) van Hattum''' (born 17 November 1958 in [[New Plymouth]]) is a former [[New Zealand]] [[football (soccer)|football]] player who was a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] during the country's first [[Football World Cup|World Cup]] finals tournament in 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=59/teams/team=43978.html|title=1982 World Cup - New Zealand squad|author=|
publisher=FIFA.com|date=|accessdate=}}</ref> His international career started in 1980, and he played a total of 41 times for his country including unofficial matches.<ref name=rsssf>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/nz-players-careers.html|title=New Zealand Players' Careers|author=|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|date=|accessdate=5 Aug 2009}}</ref>

==Career==
Van Hattum made his official [[All Whites]] debut in a 2-0 win over [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]] on 21 February 1980<ref name=alup>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id1563.htm|title=A-International Lineups, 1980-1989|author=|publisher=The Ultimate New Zealand Soccer Website|date=|accessdate=5 Aug 2009}}</ref> and ended his international playing career with 28 A-international caps to his credit,<ref name=aapp>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimatenzsoccer.com/NZRepSoccer/id1708.htm|title=A-International Appearances - Overall|author=|publisher=The Ultimate New Zealand Soccer Website|date=|accessdate=5 Aug 2009}}</ref> his final cap an appearance in a 1-2 loss to [[Australia national football team|Australia]] on 2 November 1986.<ref name=alup />

Controversially, van Hattum replaced [[Richard Wilson (footballer)|Richard Wilson]] as goalkeeper for all three games at the finals tournament in [[1982 FIFA World Cup|Spain]]<ref name=wcf>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/culture/1982-soccer-world-cup/the-finals-games|title=The 1982 World Cup finals|work=New Zealand History Online|date=1 May 2008|accessdate = 5 Aug 2009}}</ref> despite Wilson's having played in all fifteen of New Zealand's qualifying matches.<ref>{{cite news
| title = New Zealand 1982 World Cup squad
| url = http://www.nzsoccer.com/page/1982_world_cup_team.html
| publisher = New Zealand Football
| accessdate = 4 July 2008}}</ref>

Van Hattum was rated 2nd behind [[Mark Bosnich]] of [[Australia]] in the Oceania Goalkeeper of the Century category in [[IFFHS|International Federation of Football History and Statistics]]' Century Elections.<ref>{{cite news
| title = IFFHS' Century Elections
| url = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/iffhs-century.html#ockoy
| publisher = IFFHS
| accessdate = 4 July 2008}}</ref>

Serving as a director on the [[New Zealand Football|New Zealand Football Board]], van Hattum stood for re-election at the AGM for an expected board shake-up and was elected Chairman of the seven person board on 25 June 2008.
<ref>{{cite news
| title = NZF Administration
| url = http://www.nzsoccer.com/page/nzf_administration.html
| publisher = New Zealand Football
| accessdate = 28 June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
| title = Van Hattum takes chair at New Zealand Football
| url = http://nzsoccer.com/plugins/newsfeed.cgi?rm=content&plugin_data_id=23956
| publisher = New Zealand Football
| accessdate = 28 June 2008}}</ref>

==Family==
Two of his sisters, [[Marie-Jose Cooper]] and [[Grazia MacIntosh]], also represented New Zealand with the [[New Zealand women's national football team]], the ''Football Ferns''.<ref>[http://www.nzsoccer.com/page/caps_and_goals.html NZ Ferns Caps and Goals]</ref> His youngest Sister, Stella Pennell (prev. Stella Lenihan/ n<U+00E9>e van Hattum) represented New Zealand with the New Zealand Karate Federation - first as competitor, then as Women's coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/sport/2503216/The-father-of-football|title=Father of Football|author=|publisher=Taranaki Daily News|date=15 June 2009|accessdate=}}</ref>

